# =============================================================================
# SCRIPTED EVENT: Gulf of Tonkin, August 1964
# =============================================================================

@lbj_ev_tonkin_trigger
title: The Gulf of Tonkin
on-arrival: lbj_ev_tonkin = 1
go-to: lbj_ev_tonkin_scene

@lbj_ev_tonkin_scene
title: Two Attacks, or One, or None
new-page: true

McNamara is on the phone. It is 9:43 p.m.

The USS Maddox was attacked two days ago. That is certain. Tonight, the Turner Joy is reporting a second attack — torpedoes in the water, enemy vessels. The captain of the Turner Joy is, McNamara says, very confident.

You will learn later, after it is too late for learning to help, that the sonar operator on the Turner Joy was twenty-three years old and may have been tracking his own ship's wake.

But that is later. Right now, McNamara is on the phone, the Joint Chiefs are ready, and Congress is asking what you're going to do.

What you're going to do, you have already decided. The question is how clearly you've decided it.

- @lbj_tonkin_resolution: Request a blank-check resolution from Congress.
- @lbj_tonkin_limited: Respond proportionally without the resolution.
- @lbj_tonkin_investigate: Wait. Verify the second attack before acting.

@lbj_tonkin_resolution
title: The Resolution
on-arrival: lbj_vietnam += 18; lbj_military -= 8; lbj_capital += 5; lbj_credibility -= 8; lbj_coup -= 3; lbj_antiwar += 5; lbj_casualties += 4

The Gulf of Tonkin Resolution passes 98-2. Wayne Morse and Ernest Gruening vote no. You will not forget their names.

You now have, effectively, a declaration of war without a declaration of war. The Joint Chiefs have plans. The plans involve numbers: troop numbers, sortie numbers, body count numbers.

You tell yourself you will use it carefully. That is what everyone tells himself.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_tonkin_limited
title: Measured Response
on-arrival: lbj_vietnam += 8; lbj_military += 5; lbj_credibility -= 3; lbj_antiwar += 2; lbj_casualties += 2

You authorize air strikes. Proportional. Controlled. You do not ask for a resolution.

You will need more authority later. You will get it. But for now, you have not handed Congress a blank check, and you have not handed the military a license.

McNamara looks at you with something that might be respect, or might be patience.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_tonkin_investigate
title: Verify First
on-arrival: lbj_credibility += 6; lbj_military += 8; lbj_approval -= 3; lbj_antiwar -= 3; lbj_coup += 4

You ask for another twelve hours. McNamara is unhappy. The Joint Chiefs are unhappy. The Republicans are calling you weak.

What the additional hours reveal is ambiguous, which is its own kind of answer. You respond proportionally and do not claim certainty you don't have.

The far right begins a murmur that you lack resolve. It will get louder.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

# =============================================================================
# CARD: McNamara's Metrics
# =============================================================================

@lbj_vietnam_mcnamara
title: McNamara's Numbers
is-card: true
card-image: img/mcnamara_card.png
tags: lbj_vietnam_card
max-visits: 5

He comes in with the briefing book. He always comes in with the briefing book. Robert McNamara, Secretary of Defense, Ford Motor Company president, the man who brought statistical management to the Pentagon.

The charts are excellent. The metrics are rigorous. The kill ratios are favorable. The pacification percentages are improving. The number of hamlets under South Vietnamese government control is up.

You have a nagging feeling about the hamlets.

- @lbj_mcnamara_trust: Accept the metrics. Escalate based on the data.
- @lbj_mcnamara_probe: Push back. Ask the questions that aren't in the briefing book.
- @lbj_mcnamara_westmoreland: Ask Westmoreland directly. Go around McNamara.

@lbj_mcnamara_trust
title: Trust the System
on-arrival: lbj_vietnam += 7; lbj_military -= 3; lbj_casualties += 3; lbj_credibility -= 3; lbj_antiwar += 4

You authorize the additional troop deployments McNamara's numbers support.

The metrics continue to look good. The war does not appear to be ending.

You have a meeting next month. The metrics will look good then too. This is beginning to feel like a particular kind of trap.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_mcnamara_probe
title: Question the Numbers
on-arrival: lbj_capital -= 6; lbj_military += 6; lbj_credibility += 4; lbj_coup += 2

You ask about the hamlets. You ask how they are defining "under government control." You ask who is doing the counting.

McNamara is too intelligent to be offended. He is also too committed to his own framework to take the question where it leads. He schedules a follow-up briefing.

The follow-up briefing has better charts.

You are beginning to understand that you are going to be here for a while.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_mcnamara_westmoreland
title: The General's View
on-arrival: lbj_vietnam += 5; lbj_military -= 6; lbj_coup += 4; lbj_casualties += 2

Westmoreland tells you what you want to hear, but differently. The metrics are different. The conclusion is the same: more troops, more time, more resources, eventual success.

You notice that his certainty does not diminish when you ask the harder questions. This is either the confidence of a man who knows what he's doing, or something else entirely.

McNamara finds out you went around him. He doesn't say anything. He doesn't have to.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

# =============================================================================
# CARD: The Draft
# =============================================================================

@lbj_vietnam_draft
title: The Draft Notice
is-card: true
card-image: img/draft_card.png
tags: lbj_vietnam_card
view-if: lbj_vietnam >= 25
max-visits: 3

The numbers don't work without the draft. Westmoreland is asking for more men than volunteers can provide.

Three hundred thousand young Americans will receive notices this year. They will go to Vietnam, or they will go to Canada, or they will go to college and get a deferment, or they will find a sympathetic doctor. The system of who goes and who doesn't is not, everyone understands, entirely fair.

Nobody says this on the record.

- @lbj_vietnam_draft_expand: Expand the draft. The war needs the men.
- @lbj_vietnam_draft_lottery: Push for a lottery system. Make it fairer.
- @lbj_vietnam_draft_deferments: Leave the deferment system as is.

@lbj_vietnam_draft_expand
title: More Men
on-arrival: lbj_vietnam += 5; lbj_casualties += 5; lbj_antiwar += 10; lbj_liberals -= 6; lbj_labor -= 4; lbj_military -= 5; lbj_far_right -= 3

The notices go out. The buses leave. The news from Vietnam is mixed, which McNamara says is better than it sounds.

The campuses are going to get louder. You can hear it already.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_vietnam_draft_lottery
title: The Lottery
on-arrival: lbj_capital -= 8; lbj_antiwar -= 5; lbj_liberals += 4; lbj_credibility += 5; lbj_casualties += 3

A lottery is at least honest. Your birthday goes into a drum. The unfairness becomes random rather than economic.

The campuses are still angry. But the argument has changed slightly, and in politics, changing the argument is sometimes the best you can do.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_vietnam_draft_deferments
title: As Is
on-arrival: lbj_antiwar += 7; lbj_liberals -= 3; lbj_credibility -= 4; lbj_dixiecrats += 2; lbj_labor -= 3

The sons of men who can afford doctors and college continue to avoid the war. The sons of men who cannot continue to go.

The labor movement notices this before the press does. They will not say so at AFL-CIO meetings, but they are doing the arithmetic.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

# =============================================================================
# CARD: De-escalation Window
# =============================================================================

@lbj_vietnam_deescalate
title: The Way Out
is-card: true
card-image: img/deescalate_card.png
tags: lbj_vietnam_card
view-if: lbj_vietnam >= 30
max-visits: 2

Clark Clifford has been asking questions you don't like. The questions are: what does victory look like? How do you define it? How do you know when you've achieved it?

Clifford is a hawk who has looked at the numbers and is starting to sound like a dove. This concerns you more than any protest.

There is a window. The North Vietnamese are talking, in the way that parties who are not ready to stop fighting but are ready to talk talk. It would mean something, giving up something, to walk through it.

- @lbj_vietnam_deescalate_yes: Begin winding down. Negotiate seriously.
- @lbj_vietnam_deescalate_no: Stay the course. Withdrawal is surrender.
- @lbj_vietnam_deescalate_secret: Begin secret back-channel talks.

@lbj_vietnam_deescalate_yes
title: Begin the Exit
on-arrival: lbj_vietnam -= 15; lbj_antiwar -= 12; lbj_liberals += 10; lbj_military += 15; lbj_coup += 8; lbj_credibility -= 5; lbj_far_right += 10; lbj_unity += 4

You announce a halt to the bombing. You say you are ready to negotiate. The doves call it courage. The hawks call it surrender. The North Vietnamese send negotiators to Paris.

The talks go slowly. The war does not end overnight. But the trajectory has changed, and you feel it in the briefing room — a different kind of tension, the tension of men who thought they had more time.

Certain generals are quieter than usual in the weeks that follow.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_vietnam_deescalate_no
title: Stay the Course
on-arrival: lbj_vietnam += 5; lbj_antiwar += 8; lbj_military -= 5; lbj_casualties += 5; lbj_credibility -= 6; lbj_liberals -= 8

You are not going to be the president who lost Vietnam. You have said this to yourself in the mirror. You have said it to Lady Bird, who has not responded in the way you hoped.

The war continues. The metrics continue to look promising. The body counts continue.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_vietnam_deescalate_secret
title: Paris Back Channel
on-arrival: lbj_capital -= 10; lbj_credibility -= 2; lbj_antiwar -= 4; lbj_coup += 3; lbj_coup_hints += 1

Averell Harriman flies to Paris with instructions he does not write down.

The conversations happen. They are slow. They are deniable. They are real.

Someone at State is asking why the Paris station's cable traffic has increased. It's the kind of question that gets asked by someone who is either doing their job or something else.

You don't pursue it.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

