# SCRIPTED EVENT: Tet Offensive, February 1968
# =============================================================================

@lbj_ev_tet_trigger
title: Tet
on-arrival: lbj_ev_tet = 1; lbj_vietnam += 5; lbj_antiwar += 22; lbj_credibility -= 20; lbj_unity -= 12; lbj_military += 10; lbj_approval -= 15; lbj_liberals -= 10
go-to: lbj_ev_tet_scene

@lbj_ev_tet_scene
title: Tet, 1968
new-page: true

On the Vietnamese New Year, the North Vietnamese and Viet Cong launch simultaneous attacks on more than a hundred cities and towns across South Vietnam. They attack the American Embassy in Saigon. The fighting goes on for weeks.

Militarily, it is a failure for them. Westmoreland will say this. McNamara will say this.

On television, it looks like something else.

Walter Cronkite goes to Vietnam. He comes back and says, on the CBS Evening News, that the war appears to be a stalemate. Six months ago, your administration was telling America the war was being won.

Sixty percent of Americans trust Walter Cronkite. You know the number. You have always known the number.

*"If I've lost Cronkite,"* you say to no one in particular, *"I've lost Middle America."*

- @lbj_tet_respond_military: Respond militarily. Double down. Win the argument with results.
- @lbj_tet_respond_reassess: Reassess. Clifford's questions start getting better answers.
- @lbj_tet_respond_withdraw: Announce you will not run in 1968. Step aside.

@lbj_tet_respond_military
title: Fight Through It
on-arrival: lbj_vietnam += 10; lbj_casualties += 8; lbj_antiwar += 10; lbj_credibility -= 8; lbj_military -= 5; lbj_unity -= 5

You authorize Westmoreland's request for two hundred thousand more troops.

The press covers the request as evidence that the war is going badly, which is, you have to admit, a reasonable interpretation.

The credibility gap is no longer a gap. It is a canyon. People are using that word now — the credibility gap — in headlines.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_tet_respond_reassess
title: Clifford's Review
on-arrival: lbj_vietnam -= 8; lbj_antiwar -= 8; lbj_credibility += 4; lbj_liberals += 6; lbj_military += 8; lbj_coup += 5; lbj_unity += 3

You ask Clifford to conduct a fundamental reassessment of the war. He does. He reports back what you suspected: there is no military path to the outcome you've been describing.

The Joint Chiefs receive this news with a stillness that reminds you of something you can't quite name.

You begin the long, halting process of withdrawal.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_tet_respond_withdraw
title: March 31
on-arrival: lbj_vietnam -= 12; lbj_antiwar -= 15; lbj_liberals += 8; lbj_approval += 6; lbj_unity += 5; lbj_military += 12; lbj_coup += 6; lbj_jfk_shadow -= 20
new-page: true

On the evening of March 31, 1968, you address the nation.

You announce a unilateral halt to bombing over most of North Vietnam. You announce your intention to negotiate.

And then: *"I shall not seek, and I will not accept, the nomination of my party for another term as your President."*

Lady Bird is in the room. She looks relieved in a way she has been trying not to show for months.

You are sixty years old. You are going home.

- @lbj_main_hand: The final months

